Snooker


Snooker (pronounced UK: /ˈsnuːkə/, US: /ˈsnʊkər/){"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.macmillandictionary.com/pronunciation/british/snooker", "title": "Pronunciation of ''snooker''", "publisher": "Macmillan Publishers", "location": "London, UK", "accessdate": "19 March 2012", "urlstatus": "live", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20120415162427/http://www.macmillandictionary.com/pronunciation/british/snooker", "work": "Macmillan Dictionary"}{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.macmillandictionary.com/pronunciation/american/snooker", "title": "American pronunciation of ''snooker''", "publisher": "op. cit.", "accessdate": "19 March 2012", "urlstatus": "live", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20130512225433/http://www.macmillandictionary.com/pronunciation/american/snooker", "work": "Macmillan Dictionary"} is a cue sport that originated among British Army officers stationed in India in the second half of the 19th century. It is played on a rectangular table covered with a green cloth (or "baize"), with pockets at each of the four corners and in the middle of each long side. Using a cue stick and 21 coloured balls, players must strike the white ball (or "cue ball") to pot or pocket the remaining balls in the correct sequence, accumulating points for each pot. An individual game (or frame), is won by the player scoring the most points. A match is won when a player wins a predetermined number of frames.
Snooker gained its identity in 1875 when army officer Sir Neville Chamberlain (1856–1944), stationed in Ooty, Tamil Nadu, devised a set of rules that combined pyramid and black pool. The word snooker was a long-used military term for inexperienced or first-year personnel. The game grew in popularity in the United Kingdom, and the Billiards Association and Control Club was formed in 1919. It is now governed by the World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association (WPBSA).
The World Snooker Championship has taken place since 1927. Joe Davis, a key figure and pioneer in the early growth of the sport, won the championship 15 straight times between 1927 and 1946. The "modern era" began in 1969 after the broadcaster BBC commissioned the snooker television show Pot Black and later began to air the World Championship in 1978. Key figures in the game were Ray Reardon in the 1970s, Steve Davis in the 1980s, and Stephen Hendry in the 1990s, each winning six or more World championships. Since 2000, Ronnie O'Sullivan has won the most world titles, with five. Top professional players now compete regularly around the world and earn millions of pounds on the World Snooker Tour, which features players from across the world.

History
The origin of snooker dates back to the latter half of the 19th century.{"citetype": "web", "url": "https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/sporting-vernacular-11-snooker-1089731.html", "title": "Sporting Vernacular 11. Snooker", "last": "Maume", "first": "Chris", "date": "25 April 1999", "accessdate": "25 February 2007", "urlstatus": "live", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20170211083228/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/sporting-vernacular-11-snooker-1089731.html", "work": "The Independent"} In the 1870s, billiards was a popular activity among British Army officers stationed in India, and several variations of the game were devised during this time.{"citetype": "web", "url": "https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/sporting-vernacular-11-snooker-1089731.html", "title": "Sporting Vernacular 11. Snooker", "last": "Maume", "first": "Chris", "date": "25 April 1999", "accessdate": "25 February 2007", "urlstatus": "live", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20170211083228/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/sporting-vernacular-11-snooker-1089731.html", "work": "The Independent"} One variation that originated at the officers' mess of the 11th Devonshire Regiment in 1875{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.snookerheritage.co.uk/normans-articles/days-of-old/origins-of-snooker/", "title": "Origins of Snooker", "last": "Clare", "first": "Peter", "date": "2008", "publisher": "Snooker Heritage", "accessdate": "8 February 2017", "urlstatus": "live", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20170103150005/http://snookerheritage.co.uk/normans-articles/days-of-old/origins-of-snooker/"} combined the rules of two pocket billiards games: pyramid and black pool.{"citetype": "book", "last1": "Moreman", "first1": "T. R.", "date": "25 May 2006", "chapter": "Chamberlain, Sir Neville Francis Fitzgerald (1856\u20131944), army officer and inventor of snooker", "title": "Oxford Dictionary of National Biography", "publisher": "Oxford University Press"}{"citetype": "web", "url": "https://www.wpbsa.com/about/history/full-history-of-snooker/", "title": "Full History of Snooker - WPBSA", "accessdate": "16 September 2019", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20190810132854/http://www.wpbsa.com/about/history/full-history-of-snooker/", "archivedate": "10 August 2019", "work": "WPBSA"} The former was played with fifteen red coloured balls positioned in a triangle, while the latter involved the potting of designated balls.{"citetype": "web", "url": "https://www.wpbsa.com/about/history/full-history-of-snooker/", "title": "Full History of Snooker - WPBSA", "accessdate": "16 September 2019", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20190810132854/http://www.wpbsa.com/about/history/full-history-of-snooker/", "archivedate": "10 August 2019", "work": "WPBSA"}{"citetype": "book", "last1": "Shamos", "first1": "Mike", "date": "1994", "title": "Pool", "url": "https://archive.org/details/poolhistorystrat0000sham", "location": "New York City", "publisher": "Friedman Fairfax", "ref": "Shamos 1994", "urlaccess": "registration"} The game was developed in 1884 when its first set of rules was finalised by Sir Neville Chamberlain,[a] an English army officer who helped develop and popularise the game at Stone House in Ooty (Ootacamund) on a table built by Burroughes & Watts that was brought over by boat.{"citetype": "news", "date": "16 June 2014", "title": "Ooty, India: back in time to the birthplace of snooker", "url": "https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/asia/india/articles/Ooty-India-back-in-time-to-the-birthplace-of-snooker/", "urlstatus": "live", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20170321074803/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/asia/india/articles/Ooty-India-back-in-time-to-the-birthplace-of-snooker/", "accessdate": "8 February 2017", "newspaper": "The Telegraph", "first": "Martin", "last": "Hughes-Games"}
The word snooker was a slang term for first-year cadets and inexperienced military personnel, but Chamberlain would often use it for the performance of one of his fellow officers at the table.{"citetype": "web", "url": "https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/sporting-vernacular-11-snooker-1089731.html", "title": "Sporting Vernacular 11. Snooker", "last": "Maume", "first": "Chris", "date": "25 April 1999", "accessdate": "25 February 2007", "urlstatus": "live", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20170211083228/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/sporting-vernacular-11-snooker-1089731.html", "work": "The Independent"} In 1887, snooker was given its first definite reference in England in a copy of Sporting Life which caused a growth in popularity.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.snookerheritage.co.uk/normans-articles/days-of-old/origins-of-snooker/", "title": "Origins of Snooker", "last": "Clare", "first": "Peter", "date": "2008", "publisher": "Snooker Heritage", "accessdate": "8 February 2017", "urlstatus": "live", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20170103150005/http://snookerheritage.co.uk/normans-articles/days-of-old/origins-of-snooker/"} Chamberlain came out as the game's inventor in a letter to The Field published on 19 March 1938, 63 years after the fact.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.snookerheritage.co.uk/normans-articles/days-of-old/origins-of-snooker/", "title": "Origins of Snooker", "last": "Clare", "first": "Peter", "date": "2008", "publisher": "Snooker Heritage", "accessdate": "8 February 2017", "urlstatus": "live", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20170103150005/http://snookerheritage.co.uk/normans-articles/days-of-old/origins-of-snooker/"}
Snooker grew in popularity across the Indian colonies and the United Kingdom, but it remained a game mainly for the gentry, and many gentlemen's clubs that had a billiards table would not allow non-members inside to play.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.snookerheritage.co.uk/normans-articles/days-of-old/origins-of-snooker/", "title": "Origins of Snooker", "last": "Clare", "first": "Peter", "date": "2008", "publisher": "Snooker Heritage", "accessdate": "8 February 2017", "urlstatus": "live", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20170103150005/http://snookerheritage.co.uk/normans-articles/days-of-old/origins-of-snooker/"} To accommodate the growing interest, smaller and more open snooker-specific clubs were formed.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.snookerheritage.co.uk/normans-articles/days-of-old/origins-of-snooker/", "title": "Origins of Snooker", "last": "Clare", "first": "Peter", "date": "2008", "publisher": "Snooker Heritage", "accessdate": "8 February 2017", "urlstatus": "live", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20170103150005/http://snookerheritage.co.uk/normans-articles/days-of-old/origins-of-snooker/"} In 1919, the Billiards Association and the Billiards Control Board merged to form the Billiards Association and Control Club (BA&CC) and a new, standard set of rules for snooker first became official.[10]
In 1927 the first World Snooker Championship was organised by Joe Davis.{"citetype": "web", "url": "https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/sporting-vernacular-11-snooker-1089731.html", "title": "Sporting Vernacular 11. Snooker", "last": "Maume", "first": "Chris", "date": "25 April 1999", "accessdate": "25 February 2007", "urlstatus": "live", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20170211083228/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/sporting-vernacular-11-snooker-1089731.html", "work": "The Independent"}[b] Davis, as a professional English billiards and snooker player, moved the game from a pastime to a professional activity.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.cuesnviews.co.uk/Snooker/timeline.htm", "title": "Cues n Views - History Page, timeline", "last": "Smith", "first": "John A", "accessdate": "24 February 2007", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20060216115629/http://www.cuesnviews.co.uk/Snooker/timeline.htm", "quote": "Joe Davis will reinvent this after-dinner pastime and become world champion", "work": "cuesnviews.co.uk"} Davis won every world championship until 1946, when he retired from the championships.{"citetype": "news", "date": "7 October 1946", "page": "8", "newspaper": "The Times"} The game went into a decline through the 1950s and 1960s with little interest generated outside of those who played.{"citetype": "news", "date": "11 March 1968", "title": "Snooker win to Pulman", "url": "https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ZvlXAAAAIBAJ&sjid=uOcDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5826%2C3589905", "page": "12", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20160301135415/https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ZvlXAAAAIBAJ&sjid=uOcDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5826%2C3589905", "archivedate": "1 March 2016", "accessdate": "16 September 2019", "newspaper": "[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]"}{"citetype": "web", "url": "https://www.wpbsa.com/about/history/full-history-of-snooker/", "title": "Full History of Snooker - WPBSA", "accessdate": "16 September 2019", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20190810132854/http://www.wpbsa.com/about/history/full-history-of-snooker/", "archivedate": "10 August 2019", "work": "WPBSA"} In 1959, Davis introduced a variation of the game known as "Snooker Plus" to try to improve the game's popularity by adding two extra colours, but this failed to gain interest.{"citetype": "news", "date": "27 October 1959", "title": "Snooker Plus", "url": "https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=p3dAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=dKMMAAAAIBAJ&pg=2895%2C8253550", "page": "10", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20160505071329/https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=p3dAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=dKMMAAAAIBAJ&pg=2895,8253550", "archivedate": "5 May 2016", "accessdate": "27 November 2019", "newspaper": "[[The Glasgow Herald]]"}{"citetype": "news", "date": "27 October 1959", "page": "17", "newspaper": "The Times"}
In 1969, David Attenborough commissioned the snooker television series Pot Black to demonstrate the potential of colour television, with the green table and multi-coloured balls being ideal for showing off the advantages of colour broadcasting.{"citetype": "web", "url": "https://www.wpbsa.com/about/history/full-history-of-snooker/", "title": "Full History of Snooker - WPBSA", "accessdate": "16 September 2019", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20190810132854/http://www.wpbsa.com/about/history/full-history-of-snooker/", "archivedate": "10 August 2019", "work": "WPBSA"}{"citetype": "news", "date": "27 October 2005", "title": "Pot Black returns", "url": "http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/4382776.stm", "work": "news.bbc.co.uk", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20061117104945/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/4382776.stm", "archivedate": "17 November 2006", "accessdate": "31 January 2019"}[18] The series became a ratings success and was for a time the second-most popular show on BBC2.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.fcsnooker.co.uk/general%20interest/pot_black.html", "title": "Pot Black Ratings", "last": "Callan", "first": "Frank", "date": "15 March 2007", "accessdate": "13 November 2017", "urlstatus": "dead", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20070315035635/http://www.fcsnooker.co.uk/general%20interest/pot_black.html", "archivedate": "15 March 2007", "work": "FCSnooker.co.uk"} Interest in the game increased and the 1978 World Snooker Championship was the first to be fully televised.{"citetype": "news", "date": "5 May 2002", "title": "World Championships 2002 {{!}} Take snooker to the world", "url": "http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/world_champs_2002/1959780.stm", "work": "news.bbc.co.uk", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20070225160919/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/world_champs_2002/1959780.stm", "archivedate": "25 February 2007", "accessdate": "31 January 2019"}{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.offthetelly.co.uk/features/bbc2/forty2.htm", "title": "1978&nbsp;\u2013 The World Snooker Championships", "date": "27 April 2006", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20060427132655/http://www.offthetelly.co.uk/features/bbc2/forty2.htm", "archivedate": "27 April 2006", "quote": "By 1977, though, a new lighting system had been devised, allowing the players to be seen clearly without problems and, the following year, Aubrey Singer agreed to cover the World Championships all the way through, with an hour of highlights every day for 16 days"} The game quickly became a mainstream game in the United Kingdom,{"citetype": "web", "url": "https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2004/feb/10/football.newsstory", "title": "Paul MacInnes: Can an alice band save snooker?", "last": "MacInnes", "first": "Paul", "accessdate": "16 September 2019", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20160722062340/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2004/feb/10/football.newsstory", "archivedate": "22 July 2016", "work": "the Guardian"} Ireland and much of the Commonwealth, and has enjoyed much success since the late 1970s, with most of the ranking tournaments being televised.{"citetype": "web", "url": "https://www.wpbsa.com/about/history/full-history-of-snooker/", "title": "Full History of Snooker - WPBSA", "accessdate": "16 September 2019", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20190810132854/http://www.wpbsa.com/about/history/full-history-of-snooker/", "archivedate": "10 August 2019", "work": "WPBSA"} By the 1985 World Snooker Championship a total of 18.5 million viewers watched the concluding frame of the final between Dennis Taylor and Steve Davis, a record viewership for the United Kingdom for any broadcast after midnight.{"citetype": "news", "date": "18 April 2003", "title": "1985: The black ball final", "url": "http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/2953933.stm", "work": "news.bbc.co.uk", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20030924005037/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/2953933.stm", "archivedate": "24 September 2003", "accessdate": "31 January 2019"}{"citetype": "web", "title": "Great Sporting Moments: Dennis Taylor defeats Steve Davis 18\u201317 at the", "date": "12 July 2009", "accessdate": "4 September 2019", "work": "The Independent"} In the early 2000s, a ban on tobacco advertising led to a decrease in the number of professional tournaments,{"citetype": "web", "url": "https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2006/jan/19/snooker.gdnsport31", "title": "Snooker: World championship finds new sponsors", "accessdate": "31 January 2019", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20160325161804/http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2006/jan/19/snooker.gdnsport31", "archivedate": "25 March 2016", "work": "the Guardian"} with professional tournaments being cut to only 15 events in 2003, from 22 in 1999.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.snooker.org/Trn/9899/diary9899.shtml", "title": "WWW Snooker: Tournament Diary 1998/99", "accessdate": "16 September 2019", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20190213172612/http://www.snooker.org/Trn/9899/diary9899.shtml", "archivedate": "13 February 2019", "work": "snooker.org"}{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.snooker.org/trn/0304/", "title": "WWW Snooker: The 2003/2004 Season", "accessdate": "16 September 2019", "archiveurl": "https://www.webcitation.org/67oAU7qAv?url=http://www.snooker.org/trn/0304/", "archivedate": "20 May 2012", "work": "snooker.org"} However, the popularity of the game in Asia, with emerging talents such as Liang Wenbo and more established players such as Ding Junhui and Marco Fu, boosted the sport in the Far East.{"citetype": "news", "date": "22 January 2007", "title": "China in Ding's hands", "url": "http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/6288739.stm", "work": "news.bbc.co.uk", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20070827174441/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/6288739.stm", "archivedate": "27 August 2007", "accessdate": "31 January 2019"}{"citetype": "news", "date": "4 April 2005", "title": "Could Ding be snooker's saviour?", "url": "http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/4408523.stm", "work": "news.bbc.co.uk", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20101127141717/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/4408523.stm", "archivedate": "27 November 2010", "accessdate": "31 January 2019"} By 2007, the BBC dedicated 400 hours to snooker coverage, compared to just 14 minutes 40 years earlier.{"citetype": "web", "url": "https://www.nytimes.com/2006/07/16/sports/othersports/16spencer.html", "title": "John Spencer, 71, Dies; Helped Popularize Snooker", "date": "16 July 2006", "accessdate": "26 April 2018", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20180423040650/https://www.nytimes.com/2006/07/16/sports/othersports/16spencer.html", "archivedate": "23 April 2018", "work": "The New York Times"}
In 2010, promoter Barry Hearn gained a controlling interest in World Snooker Ltd. and the World Snooker Tour, pledging to revitalise the "moribund" professional game.{"citetype": "news", "date": "2 June 2010", "title": "Barry Hearn wins vote to take control of World Snooker", "url": "http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/8712167.stm", "work": "BBC", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20100923132449/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/8712167.stm", "archivedate": "23 September 2010", "accessdate": "31 January 2019"}{"citetype": "news", "date": "27 November 2013", "title": "Barry Hearn: World Snooker chief on how he saved the sport", "url": "https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/25108165", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20151016034358/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/25108165", "archivedate": "16 October 2015", "accessdate": "31 January 2019", "newspaper": "BBC Sport"}{"citetype": "web", "url": "https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2010/jun/02/barry-hearn-world-snooker", "title": "Barry Hearn wins vote to take control of World Snooker", "accessdate": "16 September 2019", "work": "the Guardian"} Since this time, the number of professional tournaments has increased, with 44 events in the 2019/20 season.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?season=2019&template=2", "title": "Calendar 2019/2020 - snooker.org", "language": "no", "accessdate": "16 September 2019", "work": "snooker.org"} Events have also been made to be more suitable for television broadcasts, such as the Snooker Shoot-Out, a timed, one-frame tournament.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.worldsnooker.com/tickets/2019-snooker-shoot-out/", "title": "2019 BetVictor Shoot Out - World Snooker", "accessdate": "16 September 2019", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20190711043029/http://www.worldsnooker.com/tickets/2019-snooker-shoot-out/", "archivedate": "11 July 2019", "work": "World Snooker"} Prize money for professional events has also increased, with top players making several million pounds during their careers.{"citetype": "news", "date": "8 July 2019", "title": "World Snooker prize money increase highlights growth, says Barry Hearn", "url": "https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/48909960", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20190829000907/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/48909960", "archivedate": "29 August 2019", "accessdate": "16 September 2019", "newspaper": "BBC Sport"} The winner of the 2020 World Snooker Championship will receive £500,000 out of a total fund of £2,395,000.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.worldsnooker.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Click-here-for-the-full-prize-money-schedule-2.pdf", "title": "2019\u20132020 Season Summary", "accessdate": "30 July 2019", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20190719025727/http://www.worldsnooker.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Click-here-for-the-full-prize-money-schedule-2.pdf", "archivedate": "19 July 2019", "work": "worldsnooker.com"}

Objective
The objective of the game is to score more points than one's opponent by potting object balls in the correct order. At the start of a frame, the balls are positioned as shown in the first image, and the players then take turns hitting shots by striking the cue ball with the tip of the cue, their aim being to pot one of the red balls into a pocket and thereby score a point. Failure to make contact with the red ball constitutes a foul shot.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.wpbsa.com/sites/default/files/uploads/official_rules_edited_05.11.14_web_version_1.pdf", "title": "Official Rules of the Games of Snooker and English Billiards", "date": "November 2014", "publisher": "[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|The World Professional Billiards & Snooker Association Limited]]", "accessdate": "23 April 2016", "urlstatus": "dead", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20160304084316/http://www.wpbsa.com/sites/default/files/uploads/official_rules_edited_05.11.14_web_version_1.pdf", "archivedate": "4 March 2016"} If the striker pots a red ball, he or she must then pot one of the six "colours".[c] If the player successfully pots a colour, the value of that ball is added to the player's score, and the ball is returned to its starting position on the table. After that, the player must pot another red ball, then another colour, in sequence. This process continues until the striker fails to pot the desired ball, at which point the opponent comes to the table to play the next shot.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.wpbsa.com/sites/default/files/uploads/official_rules_edited_05.11.14_web_version_1.pdf", "title": "Official Rules of the Games of Snooker and English Billiards", "date": "November 2014", "publisher": "[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|The World Professional Billiards & Snooker Association Limited]]", "accessdate": "23 April 2016", "urlstatus": "dead", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20160304084316/http://www.wpbsa.com/sites/default/files/uploads/official_rules_edited_05.11.14_web_version_1.pdf", "archivedate": "4 March 2016"} The act of scoring sequentially in this manner is to make a break (see scoring below).{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.wpbsa.com/sites/default/files/uploads/official_rules_edited_05.11.14_web_version_1.pdf", "title": "Official Rules of the Games of Snooker and English Billiards", "date": "November 2014", "publisher": "[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|The World Professional Billiards & Snooker Association Limited]]", "accessdate": "23 April 2016", "urlstatus": "dead", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20160304084316/http://www.wpbsa.com/sites/default/files/uploads/official_rules_edited_05.11.14_web_version_1.pdf", "archivedate": "4 March 2016"}
The game continues in this manner until all the reds are potted and only the six colours are left on the table.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.wpbsa.com/sites/default/files/uploads/official_rules_edited_05.11.14_web_version_1.pdf", "title": "Official Rules of the Games of Snooker and English Billiards", "date": "November 2014", "publisher": "[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|The World Professional Billiards & Snooker Association Limited]]", "accessdate": "23 April 2016", "urlstatus": "dead", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20160304084316/http://www.wpbsa.com/sites/default/files/uploads/official_rules_edited_05.11.14_web_version_1.pdf", "archivedate": "4 March 2016"} At this point the colours must be potted in the order from least to most valuable ball, as per the table to the right. The shots are: yellow first (two points), then green (three points), brown (four points), blue (five points), pink (six points) and black (seven points), the balls not being returned to play.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.wpbsa.com/sites/default/files/uploads/official_rules_edited_05.11.14_web_version_1.pdf", "title": "Official Rules of the Games of Snooker and English Billiards", "date": "November 2014", "publisher": "[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|The World Professional Billiards & Snooker Association Limited]]", "accessdate": "23 April 2016", "urlstatus": "dead", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20160304084316/http://www.wpbsa.com/sites/default/files/uploads/official_rules_edited_05.11.14_web_version_1.pdf", "archivedate": "4 March 2016"} When the final ball is potted, the player with more points wins.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.wpbsa.com/sites/default/files/uploads/official_rules_edited_05.11.14_web_version_1.pdf", "title": "Official Rules of the Games of Snooker and English Billiards", "date": "November 2014", "publisher": "[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|The World Professional Billiards & Snooker Association Limited]]", "accessdate": "23 April 2016", "urlstatus": "dead", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20160304084316/http://www.wpbsa.com/sites/default/files/uploads/official_rules_edited_05.11.14_web_version_1.pdf", "archivedate": "4 March 2016"} If the scores are equal when all the balls have been potted, the black is placed back on its spot as a tiebreaker. In this situation, called re-spotted black, the black ball is placed on its designated spot and the cue ball is played as ball in hand. The referee then tosses a coin and the winner decides which player goes first. The frame continues until one of the players pots the black ball or commits a foul.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.wpbsa.com/sites/default/files/uploads/official_rules_edited_05.11.14_web_version_1.pdf", "title": "Official Rules of the Games of Snooker and English Billiards", "date": "November 2014", "publisher": "[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|The World Professional Billiards & Snooker Association Limited]]", "accessdate": "23 April 2016", "urlstatus": "dead", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20160304084316/http://www.wpbsa.com/sites/default/files/uploads/official_rules_edited_05.11.14_web_version_1.pdf", "archivedate": "4 March 2016"} A player may also concede a frame while on strike if he or she thinks there are not enough points available on the table to beat the opponent's score. In professional snooker this is a common occurrence.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.wpbsa.com/sites/default/files/uploads/official_rules_edited_05.11.14_web_version_1.pdf", "title": "Official Rules of the Games of Snooker and English Billiards", "date": "November 2014", "publisher": "[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|The World Professional Billiards & Snooker Association Limited]]", "accessdate": "23 April 2016", "urlstatus": "dead", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20160304084316/http://www.wpbsa.com/sites/default/files/uploads/official_rules_edited_05.11.14_web_version_1.pdf", "archivedate": "4 March 2016"}{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.rulesofsnooker.com/snooker-for-beginners.html", "title": "Snooker for beginners", "accessdate": "31 January 2019", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20190201013735/http://www.rulesofsnooker.com/snooker-for-beginners.html", "archivedate": "1 February 2019", "work": "Snooker rules and refereeing"}
Professional and competitive amateur matches are officiated by a referee. The referee also replaces the colours on the table when necessary and calls out how many points the player has scored during a break.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.sportsdefinitions.com/snooker/Scoreboard.html", "title": "What is Scoreboard in Snooker? Definition and Meaning", "publisher": "sportsdefinitions.com", "urlstatus": "live", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20160304060047/http://www.sportsdefinitions.com/snooker/Scoreboard.html"} Professional players usually play the game in a sporting manner, declaring fouls which they have committed but the referee has missed,{"citetype": "news", "title": "Mark Allen pockets \u00a370k Scottish Open title with a 'nice fluke' - BelfastTelegraph.co.uk", "url": "https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/sport/snooker/mark-allen-pockets-70k-scottish-open-title-with-a-nice-fluke-37632011.html", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20190201013259/https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/sport/snooker/mark-allen-pockets-70k-scottish-open-title-with-a-nice-fluke-37632011.html", "archivedate": "1 February 2019", "accessdate": "31 January 2019", "newspaper": "BelfastTelegraph.co.uk"} acknowledging good shots from their opponent, and holding up a hand to apologise for fortunate shots, known as "flukes".{"citetype": "news", "title": "Mark Allen pockets \u00a370k Scottish Open title with a 'nice fluke' - BelfastTelegraph.co.uk", "url": "https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/sport/snooker/mark-allen-pockets-70k-scottish-open-title-with-a-nice-fluke-37632011.html", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20190201013259/https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/sport/snooker/mark-allen-pockets-70k-scottish-open-title-with-a-nice-fluke-37632011.html", "archivedate": "1 February 2019", "accessdate": "31 January 2019", "newspaper": "BelfastTelegraph.co.uk"}

Scoring
Points in snooker are gained from potting the correct balls in sequence. The total number of consecutive points (excluding fouls) that a player amasses during one visit to the table is known as a break. A player attaining a break of 15, for example, could have reached it by potting a red then a black, then a red then a pink, before failing to pot the next red. A maximum break in snooker is achieved by potting all reds with blacks then all colours, yielding 147 points; this is often known as a "147" or just as a "maximum".{"citetype": "news", "date": "14 January 2007", "title": "Ding compiles maximum at Masters", "url": "http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/6260923.stm", "work": "news.bbc.co.uk", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20070207225605/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/6260923.stm", "archivedate": "7 February 2007", "accessdate": "31 January 2019"}
Points may also be scored in a game when a player's opponent fouls. A foul can occur for various reasons, most commonly for failing to hit the correct ball (e.g. hitting a colour first when the player was attempting to hit a red), or for sending the cue ball into a pocket. The former may occur when the player fails to escape from a "snooker" – a situation in which the previous player leaves the cue ball positioned such that no legal ball can be struck directly without obstruction by an illegal ball. Points gained from a foul vary from a minimum of four to a maximum of seven if the black ball is involved.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.wpbsa.com/sites/default/files/uploads/official_rules_edited_05.11.14_web_version_1.pdf", "title": "Official Rules of the Games of Snooker and English Billiards", "date": "November 2014", "publisher": "[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|The World Professional Billiards & Snooker Association Limited]]", "accessdate": "23 April 2016", "urlstatus": "dead", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20160304084316/http://www.wpbsa.com/sites/default/files/uploads/official_rules_edited_05.11.14_web_version_1.pdf", "archivedate": "4 March 2016"}
A foul shot that leaves no valid shot for the opponent can leave them a free ball. A free ball allows a player to use any other coloured ball in place of the shot they were supposed to play. Doing so with all 15 red balls in play can result in a break exceeding a maximum, with the highest possible being a 155 break, achieved via the opponent leaving a free ball, with the black being potted as the additional colour, and then potting 15 reds and blacks with the colours.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.wpbsa.com/sites/default/files/uploads/official_rules_edited_05.11.14_web_version_1.pdf", "title": "Official Rules of the Games of Snooker and English Billiards", "date": "November 2014", "publisher": "[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|The World Professional Billiards & Snooker Association Limited]]", "accessdate": "23 April 2016", "urlstatus": "dead", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20160304084316/http://www.wpbsa.com/sites/default/files/uploads/official_rules_edited_05.11.14_web_version_1.pdf", "archivedate": "4 March 2016"} Jamie Cope has the distinction of being the first player in snooker history to post a verified 155 break, achieved in a practice frame in 2005, with other players such as Alex Higgins also claiming to have made a similar break.{"citetype": "news", "title": "Alex Higgins: A 155 break impossible? Not for Higgy - BelfastTelegraph.co.uk", "url": "https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/alex-higgins/alex-higgins-a-155-break-impossible-not-for-higgy-28548775.html", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20190508102333/https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/alex-higgins/alex-higgins-a-155-break-impossible-not-for-higgy-28548775.html", "archivedate": "8 May 2019", "accessdate": "31 January 2019", "newspaper": "BelfastTelegraph.co.uk"}{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://punditarena.com/uncategorized/bbarry/147-is-not-snookers-maximum-break/", "title": "147 Is Not Snooker's Maximum Break", "date": "2 December 2014", "accessdate": "31 January 2019", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20190201013406/http://punditarena.com/uncategorized/bbarry/147-is-not-snookers-maximum-break/", "archivedate": "1 February 2019", "work": "Pundit Arena"}
One game, from the balls in their starting position until the last ball is potted, is called a "frame". A match generally consists of a predetermined number of frames and the player who wins the most frames wins the match. Most professional matches require a player to win five frames, and are called "best of nine" in reference to the maximum possible number of frames. Tournament finals are usually best of 17 or best of 19, while the world championship uses longer matches – ranging from best of 19 in the qualifiers and the first round up to best of 35 for the final (first to 18), and is played over four sessions of play held over two days.{"citetype": "news", "date": "2 May 2006", "title": "World title victory delights Dott", "url": "http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/4963842.stm", "work": "news.bbc.co.uk", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20070307030914/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/4963842.stm", "archivedate": "7 March 2007", "accessdate": "31 January 2019"}

Governance and tournaments
The World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association (WPBSA, also known as World Snooker), founded in 1968 as the Professional Billiard Players' Association,{"citetype": "news", "date": "16 February 2001", "title": "WPBSA v TSN", "url": "http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/1174311.stm", "work": "news.bbc.co.uk", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20030101203136/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/1174311.stm", "archivedate": "1 January 2003", "accessdate": "31 January 2019"} is the governing body for the professional competition.{"citetype": "news", "date": "7 December 2000", "title": "Snooker's biggest break", "url": "http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/1059298.stm", "work": "news.bbc.co.uk", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20031217035813/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/1059298.stm", "archivedate": "17 December 2003", "accessdate": "31 January 2019"}{"citetype": "news", "date": "13 November 2002", "title": "Snooker authorities survive bid", "url": "http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/2459069.stm", "work": "news.bbc.co.uk", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20040526051838/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/2459069.stm", "archivedate": "26 May 2004", "accessdate": "31 January 2019"}{"citetype": "news", "date": "14 November 2002", "title": "Snooker at the crossroads", "url": "http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/2478413.stm", "work": "news.bbc.co.uk", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20040711122138/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/2478413.stm", "archivedate": "11 July 2004", "accessdate": "31 January 2019"} The amateur game (including youth competition) is governed by the International Billiards and Snooker Federation (IBSF).{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.ibsf.info/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=18&Itemid=120", "title": "About Us", "date": "2017", "publisher": "[[International Billiards and Snooker Federation]]", "accessdate": "13 November 2017", "urlstatus": "live", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20170812003050/http://www.ibsf.info/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=18&Itemid=120", "work": "IBSF.info"} Events held specifically for women and events for seniors are handled by World Snooker under World Women's Snooker and the World Seniors Tour, respectively.[51][52]{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.worldsnooker.com/wpbsa-world-seniors-tour/", "title": "WPBSA World Seniors Tour - World Snooker", "date": "3 May 2018", "accessdate": "16 September 2019", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20181003113215/http://www.worldsnooker.com/wpbsa-world-seniors-tour/", "archivedate": "3 October 2018", "work": "World Snooker"} The highest levels of the sport are the IBSF World Snooker Championship, World Seniors Championship and the Ladies World Snooker Championship.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.worldsnooker.com/wpbsa-world-seniors-tour/", "title": "WPBSA World Seniors Tour - World Snooker", "date": "3 May 2018", "accessdate": "16 September 2019", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20181003113215/http://www.worldsnooker.com/wpbsa-world-seniors-tour/", "archivedate": "3 October 2018", "work": "World Snooker"}

Professional
Professional snooker players play on the World Snooker Tour. Events on the Tour are only open to players on the Tour and selected amateur players, but most events require qualification. Players can qualify for the Tour either by being high enough on the world rankings from prior seasons, winning continental championships, or through the Challenge Tour or Q School events.{"citetype": "web", "url": "https://www.wpbsa.com/main-tour-qualification-2019-20/", "title": "Main Tour Qualification 2019/20 - WPBSA", "accessdate": "16 September 2019", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20190407182559/https://www.wpbsa.com/main-tour-qualification-2019-20/", "archivedate": "7 April 2019", "work": "WPBSA"} Players on the Tour generally gain two-year participation for the events.{"citetype": "web", "url": "https://www.wpbsa.com/main-tour-qualification-2019-20/", "title": "Main Tour Qualification 2019/20 - WPBSA", "accessdate": "16 September 2019", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20190407182559/https://www.wpbsa.com/main-tour-qualification-2019-20/", "archivedate": "7 April 2019", "work": "WPBSA"}
Reflecting the game's aristocratic origins, the majority of tournaments on the professional circuit require players to wear waistcoats and bow ties. In recent years the necessity for this has been questioned, and players such as Stephen Maguire have been granted medical exemptions from wearing a bow tie.[55]
The Tour also has an official world rankings scheme, with only players on the Tour receiving a ranking. Ranking points, earned by players through their performances over the previous two seasons, determine the current world rankings.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.worldsnooker.com/pdfs/WSAPointsSchedule0910.pdf", "title": "Professional Tour ranking points", "publisher": "World Snooker"} A player's ranking determines what level of qualification he or she requires for specific tournaments. The elite of professional snooker are generally regarded as the "top-16" ranking players.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/5234798.stm", "title": "Swail targeting place in top 16", "date": "1 August 2006", "publisher": "BBC Sport"} They are not required to pre-qualify for some of the tournaments, such as the Shanghai Masters, the Masters and the World Snooker Championship.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/in_depth/2000/uk_championship_snooker/1039775.stm", "title": "The Seeds of Success", "date": "24 November 2000", "publisher": "BBC Sport", "accessdate": "25 February 2007", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20031018072104/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/in_depth/2000/uk_championship_snooker/1039775.stm"} Certain other events, such as those in the Coral Cup series, use the one-year ranking list to qualify; these use the results of the current season to denote participants.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://news.coral.co.uk/other/snooker/coral-cup-snooker/coral-cup-world-grand-prix-first-on-the-agenda-for-new-competition.html", "title": "Coral Cup: World Grand Prix first on the agenda for new competition", "accessdate": "16 September 2019", "work": "Coral News"} Currently, the Tour contains 125 players, with players either in the top 64 on the official ranking list, or finishing as one of the top eight prize money earners during the most recent season, guaranteed a tour place for the next season, this being assessed after the World Championship.{"citetype": "web", "url": "https://www.wpbsa.com/tour-survival-2019-five-to-go/", "title": "Tour Survival 2019: Five to Go", "website": "wpbsa.com", "publisher": "World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association"}
