Equipment
Accessories used for snooker include chalk for the tip of the cue, rests of various sorts used for playing shots that cannot be played by hand, a triangle to rack the reds, and a scoreboard. One drawback of snooker on a full-size (12 ft × 6 ft [366 cm × 183 cm]) table is the size of the room (22 by 16 feet [6.7 m × 4.9 m]), which is the minimum required for comfortable cueing room on all sides.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.thurstonsnooker.co.uk/Pages/Snookerfaq.html", "title": "Thurston Snooker Table makers", "accessdate": "25 February 2007", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20060503151323/http://www.thurstonsnooker.co.uk/Pages/Snookerfaq.html", "archivedate": "3 May 2006", "quote": "Recommended room size for full size table 22&nbsp;ft \u00d7 16&nbsp;ft", "author": "Ietswaart, Peter"} This limits the number of locations in which the game can easily be played. While pool tables are common to many pubs, snooker tends to be played either in private surroundings or in public snooker halls. The game can also be played on smaller tables using fewer red balls. Variant table sizes include 10 ft × 5 ft (305 cm × 152 cm), 9 ft × 4.5 ft (274 cm × 137 cm), 8 ft × 4 ft (244 cm × 122 cm), 6 ft × 3 ft (183 cm × 91 cm) (the smallest for realistic play) and 4 ft × 2 ft (122 cm × 61 cm). Smaller tables can come in a variety of styles, such as fold-away or dining-table convertible.{"citetype": "web", "url": "https://www.snookerandpooltablecompany.com/room-size-guide.html", "title": "Pool Table Room Size Guide - Snooker & Pool Table Company Ltd", "accessdate": "31 January 2019", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20190101051405/https://www.snookerandpooltablecompany.com/room-size-guide.html", "archivedate": "1 January 2019", "work": "snookerandpooltablecompany.com"}
A traditional snooker scoreboard resembles an abacus and records the score for each frame in units and twenties and the frame scores. They are typically attached to a wall by the snooker table. A simple scoring bead is also sometimes used, called a "scoring string", or "scoring wire".{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.sportsdefinitions.com/snooker/Scoreboard.html", "title": "What is Scoreboard in Snooker? Definition and Meaning", "publisher": "sportsdefinitions.com", "urlstatus": "live", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20160304060047/http://www.sportsdefinitions.com/snooker/Scoreboard.html"} Each bead (segment of the string) represents a single point. Snooker players typically move one or several beads with their cue.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.sportsdefinitions.com/snooker/Scoreboard.html", "title": "What is Scoreboard in Snooker? Definition and Meaning", "publisher": "sportsdefinitions.com", "urlstatus": "live", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20160304060047/http://www.sportsdefinitions.com/snooker/Scoreboard.html"}
The playing surface is 356.9 cm (11 feet 8.5 inches) by 177.8 cm (5 feet 10 inches) for a standard full-size table, with six pocket holes, one at each corner and one at the centre of each of the longer side cushions.{"citetype": "web", "url": "https://www.myactivesg.com/Sports/Billiards-and-Snooker/How-To-Play/Billiards-and-Snooker-for-Beginners/Cuesport-equipment", "title": "Cuesport equipment", "accessdate": "16 September 2019", "work": "ActiveSG"}
The fully wool cloth is usually green, with a directional nap running from the baulk end of the table towards the end with the black ball spot. The cloth is often called "baize"; although true baize is a lower quality cloth sometimes used on pool tables. The nap will affect the direction of the cue ball depending on which direction the cue ball is shot and also on whether left or right side (spin) is placed on the ball. Even if the cue ball is hit in exactly the same way, the nap will cause a different effect depending on whether the ball is hit down table (towards the black ball spot) or up table (towards the baulk line). The cloth on a snooker table is not vacuumed, as this can destroy the nap. The cloth is brushed in a straight line from the baulk end to the far end with multiple brush strokes that are straight in direction (i.e. not across the table). Some table men will also then drag a dampened cloth wrapped around a short piece of board (like a two by four), or straight back of a brush to collect any remaining fine dust and help lay the nap down. The table is then ironed. Strachan cloth, used in official snooker tournaments, is 100% wool. Some other cloths include a small percentage of nylon.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.wsptextiles.com/strachan-snooker-cloths", "title": "Strachan snooker cloths - WSP Textiles - Billiard and Tennis cloths", "urlstatus": "live", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20160209060450/http://www.wsptextiles.com/strachan-snooker-cloths", "author": "Milliken Industrials Limited - Woollen Speciality Products"}{"citetype": "web", "url": "https://archive.today/20130720150135/http://www.cuescues.co.uk/snooker-cloth/Hainsworth-Smart-Snooker-Cloth?product_id=168", "date": "10 July 2013", "accessdate": "20 July 2013", "work": "Cues Cues"}

Important players
In the professional era that began with Joe Davis in the 1930s and continues until the present day, a relatively small number of players have succeeded at the top level.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/1980218.stm", "title": "O'Sullivan in exalted company", "date": "10 May 2002", "publisher": "BBC Sport", "accessdate": "25 February 2007", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20030827090701/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/1980218.stm"}{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://news.bbc.co.uk/sportacademy/hi/sa/special_events/snooker/newsid_3986000/3986151.stm", "title": "Putting in the practice", "date": "5 November 2004", "publisher": "BBC Sport", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20151215033918/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sportacademy/hi/sa/special_events/snooker/newsid_3986000/3986151.stm", "archivedate": "15 December 2015", "author": "Hunter, Paul"} Joe Davis was world champion for twenty years, retiring unbeaten after claiming his fifteenth world title in 1946 when the tournament was reinstated after the Second World War.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/Players/DavisJ.html", "title": "Player Profile \u2013 Joe Davis OBE", "last": "Turner", "first": "Chris", "publisher": "Chris Turner's Snooker Archive", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20120510053844/http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/Players/DavisJ.html", "archivedate": "10 May 2012"} Davis was unbeaten in World Championship play, and was only ever beaten four times in his entire life, with all four defeats coming after his World Championship retirement and inflicted by his own brother Fred Davis.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/Players/DavisJ.html", "title": "Player Profile \u2013 Joe Davis OBE", "last": "Turner", "first": "Chris", "publisher": "Chris Turner's Snooker Archive", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20120510053844/http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/Players/DavisJ.html", "archivedate": "10 May 2012"} He did lose matches in handicapped tournaments, but on level terms these four defeats were the only losses of his entire career.{"citetype": "book", "date": "1979", "title": "Talking Snooker", "location": "London", "publisher": "A and C Black", "last": "Davis", "first": "Fred"} He was also world billiards champion.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/Players/DavisJ.html", "title": "Player Profile \u2013 Joe Davis OBE", "last": "Turner", "first": "Chris", "publisher": "Chris Turner's Snooker Archive", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20120510053844/http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/Players/DavisJ.html", "archivedate": "10 May 2012"}{"citetype": "book", "last1": "Gadsby", "first1": "Paul", "last2": "Williams", "first2": "Luke", "year": "2012", "title": "Snooker's World Champions: Masters of the Baize", "publisher": "Random House", "isbn": "978-1-780-57715-9"} It is regarded as highly unlikely that anyone will ever dominate the game to this level again.{"citetype": "book", "date": "1986", "title": "The History of Snooker and Billiards", "location": "Haywards Heath", "publisher": "Partridge Press", "last": "Everton", "first": "Clive"}
After Davis retired from World Championship play, the next dominant force was his younger brother Fred Davis, who had lost the 1940 final to Joe.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/Players/DavisJ.html", "title": "Player Profile \u2013 Joe Davis OBE", "last": "Turner", "first": "Chris", "publisher": "Chris Turner's Snooker Archive", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20120510053844/http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/Players/DavisJ.html", "archivedate": "10 May 2012"} By 1947, Fred Davis was deemed ready by his brother to take over the mantle, but lost the world final to the Scotsman Walter Donaldson.{"citetype": "news", "date": "22 October 1947", "title": "Davis just misses world record", "url": "http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000513/19471022/013/0002", "work": "Western Daily Press", "accessdate": "18 March 2016", "via": "[[British Newspaper Archive]]"} Davis and Donaldson would contest the next four finals. After the abandonment of the World Championship in 1953, with the 1952 final boycotted by British professionals, the World Professional Match-play Championship became the unofficial world championship.{"citetype": "book", "date": "1982", "title": "Guinness Book of Snooker", "publisher": "Guinness World Records Limited", "last": "Everton", "first": "Clive"} Fred Davis won the event every year until its penultimate one, in 1957, which he did not enter.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/world.html", "title": "World Professional Championship", "last": "Turner", "first": "Chris", "publisher": "Chris Turner's Snooker Archive", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20130416080933/http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/world.html", "archivedate": "16 April 2013", "work": "cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk"}
John Pulman was the most successful player of the 1960s, when the world championship was contested on a challenge basis.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.global-snooker.com/professional-snooker-tournaments-archive-world-championship-1964.asp", "title": "World Championship 1964", "publisher": "Global Snooker", "accessdate": "19 March 2011", "urlstatus": "dead", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20110310181405/http://www.global-snooker.com/professional-snooker-tournaments-archive-world-championship-1964.asp", "archivedate": "2011-03-10"} However, when the tournament reverted to a knockout formula in 1969, he did not prosper. Ray Reardon became the dominant force in the 1970s, winning six titles (1970, 1973–1976 and 1978), with John Spencer winning three.{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.inside-snooker.com/snooker/2014/4/8/before-the-crucible", "title": "Before the Crucible", "last": "Nunns", "first": "Hector", "date": "8 April 2014", "publisher": "Inside Snooker", "accessdate": "29 January 2016", "urlstatus": "live", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20160204210827/http://www.inside-snooker.com/snooker/2014/4/8/before-the-crucible", "archivedate": "4 February 2016"}{"citetype": "news", "date": "24 April 1976", "page": "15", "newspaper": "The Times"}
Steve Davis' first world title in 1981 made him only the 11th world champion since 1927, including the winner of the boycotted 1952 title, Horace Lindrum.{"citetype": "news", "date": "21 April 1981", "page": "1", "newspaper": "The Times"}{"citetype": "news", "date": "7 April 1981", "page": "10", "newspaper": "The Times"} Davis would win six World Championships (1981, 1983, 1984 and 1987–1989), and competed in the most watched snooker match ever, the 1985 World Snooker Championship final with Dennis Taylor.{"citetype": "news", "date": "18 April 2003", "title": "1985: The black ball final", "url": "http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/2953933.stm", "publisher": "[[BBC Sport]]", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20130928235825/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/2953933.stm", "accessdate": "4 May 2011"} Stephen Hendry became the 14th in 1990 and dominated through the 1990s, winning seven titles (1990, 1992–1996 and 1999).{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/world.html", "title": "World Professional Championship", "last": "Turner", "first": "Chris", "publisher": "Chris Turner's Snooker Archive", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20130416080933/http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/world.html", "archivedate": "16 April 2013", "work": "cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk"}{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.global-snooker.com/professional-tournaments-archive-world-championship-roll-of-honour.asp", "title": "World Championship \u2013 Roll of Honour", "publisher": "Global Snooker", "accessdate": "18 March 2013", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20120222034318/http://www.global-snooker.com/professional-tournaments-archive-world-championship-roll-of-honour.asp"} Ronnie O'Sullivan is the closest to dominance in the modern era, having won the title on five occasions in the 21st century (2001, 2004, 2008, 2012 and 2013).{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/world.html", "title": "World Professional Championship", "last": "Turner", "first": "Chris", "publisher": "Chris Turner's Snooker Archive", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20130416080933/http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/world.html", "archivedate": "16 April 2013", "work": "cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk"} Mark Williams has won three times (2000, 2003 and 2018) and John Higgins four times (1998, 2007, 2009 and 2011), but since the beginning of the century, there has not been a dominant force like in previous decades, and the modern era has seen many players playing to a similar standard, instead of one player raising the bar. Davis, for example, won more ranking tournaments than the rest of the top 64 players put together by 1985. By retaining his title in 2013, O'Sullivan became the first player to successfully defend the World Championship since Hendry in 1996 (Mark Selby would also do this in 2017).{"citetype": "web", "url": "http://www.worldsnooker.com/world_championship10_history.htm?tid=154", "title": "World Snooker Championship&nbsp;\u2013 History", "publisher": "World Snooker", "accessdate": "9 April 2010", "archiveurl": "https://web.archive.org/web/20100528154608/http://www.worldsnooker.com/world_championship10_history.htm?tid=154"}
